author: @mounsifhanafi6988
text: Hi everyone, i'm a datascientist and i can confirm what he talked about is what you need as dataScientist. You need to have in mind that in real world ( in company), collecting preparing cleaning data is what will consume 80% of your time, and dont be disppointed about it, it is part of the job, and all courses they will never talk about it. Applying machine learning algorithm is the fun part par in fact its only 20% of your job. as he said you need to be at ease web scrapping to collect data, but i will also add sql queries, spark ( you have the python version pyspark). In a fact, you will discover that you need both data engineering and Data Science skills to perform well. To finish, for beginners , at the beginning it will be hard, but it's worth it. Have fun doing Data science.

author: @tamilselvansellamuthu5950
text: Data Analyis --> Feature engineering --> Data Wrangling --> exploratory data analysis (EDA).  Programming Language --> Python --> R --> Java.  Machine Learning --> Classification --> regression --> reinforcemental --> deep learning --> Dimentionality RED --> Clustering algorithm. (libs numpy, pandas etc).  IDE --> Pycharm --> Jupyter --> Spyder.  Deploy --> AWS --> Azure --> Flask model for API consumption.  Web scraping --> Beautiful soup --> Scrapy --> urllib.  Math --> Statistics --> Linear algorithm --> Differential calculus.  Data Visualization --> Table AU --> Power BI --> Matplot lib --> ggplot --> Seaborn.    IRIS data set  House prediction

text: I think you would also want to add some database skills into this whole loop. Though there is a dedicated data Engineering team that works independently from the data science team. text: Thanks a lot for making this video!!  What I learnt here: Try to Collectively learn all the steps of Data Science instead of only learning them separately. Try to do reverse engineering of the Data Science solutions to problems, and try to think on your own on how did this happen and why was this method choosen.  Also, keep learning and applying the knowledge you learnt on other projects.  Keep an open mind, actively search for data sets to work on, learn new things by working on them.  All the best!  Have an amazing day! :) :) :)  Looking forward to learning more on Data Science! :)

text: Really depends. As the DS title is thrown around so liberally it varies from team to team. For entry level job you don‚Äôt need aws or azure unless you are applying as a data architect.
